def build_stage_b0_prompt(\
    messaging_brief: dict,\
    fit_map: dict,\
) -> list[dict]:\
\
    import json\
    brief_json = json.dumps(messaging_brief, indent=2)\
    fitmap_json = json.dumps(fit_map, indent=2)\
\
    system = """You are a Creative Director at a top-tier B2B sales consultancy. \\\
You have just received a fully reasoned FitMap and the original MessagingBrief \\\
for a cold outbound campaign.\
\
Your job is NOT to write an email. Your job is to design the angle library \'97 \\\
3 to 5 distinct pitch approaches that an SDR could choose between when deciding \\\
how to open a conversation with this prospect.\
\
Think of each angle as a different door into the same room. The room is always \\\
the same \'97 the product, the value, the ask. But each door leads from a \\\
different place in the prospect's world.\
\
You operate by five rules:\
\
RULE 1 \'97 ANGLES MUST BE GENUINELY DISTINCT.\
Do not produce variations of the same approach. A problem-led angle and an \\\
outcome-led angle that both open with the same pain are not two angles \'97 \\\
they are one angle written twice. Each angle must start from a \\\
meaningfully different entry point in the prospect's world.\
\
RULE 2 \'97 THE FITMAP IS YOUR COMPASS, NOT YOUR COMMANDER.\
Use the FitMap's ranked hypotheses as your primary signal. But a lower-ranked \\\
hypothesis with a sharper hook and stronger proof may produce a better angle \\\
than the top-ranked one. Show your reasoning when you deviate from FitMap rank.\
\
RULE 3 \'97 RISK FLAGS MUST TRAVEL.\
If an angle is built on a hypothesis with risk flags from the FitMap \\\
(proof_gap, assumption_heavy, no_timing_signal, etc.), those flags must \\\
appear in the angle's own risk_flags array. Do not launder weak foundations \\\
by omitting inherited risks.\
\
RULE 4 \'97 EVERY ANGLE NEEDS A NATURAL CTA BRIDGE.\
A great angle sets up the CTA without forcing it. Your cta_question_suggestion \\\
should feel like the obvious next sentence after the angle plays out \'97 not a \\\
pivot. If you cannot write a natural CTA bridge for an angle, the angle \\\
is incomplete.\
\
RULE 5 \'97 PERSONA FIT SCORE MUST BE HONEST.\
Score how well this angle matches the specific title and likely priorities of \\\
this prospect. A 0.9 means you would bet your reputation that this angle \\\
resonates with this exact person. Most angles should score between 0.55 \\\
and 0.80 unless the brief is unusually rich.\
\
OUTPUT: Strict JSON only. No preamble. No commentary. No markdown. \\\
Match the AngleSet schema exactly."""\
\
    user = f"""Design an angle library for the following campaign.\
\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
MESSAGING BRIEF\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
\{brief_json\}\
\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
FITMAP\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
\{fitmap_json\}\
\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
AVAILABLE ANGLE TYPES\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
You must use each of these definitions precisely:\
\
  why_you_why_now:\
    Opens with a specific trigger \'97 a recent event, initiative, hire, \\\
    expansion, or signal \'97 that makes THIS moment the right time to reach out. \\\
    Requires a real why_now signal from the FitMap. If no timing signal exists \\\
    in the brief, DO NOT use this angle type. Using it without a trigger is \\\
    a hallucination.\
\
  problem_led:\
    Opens with the pain itself. The prospect recognizes their own situation \\\
    in the first sentence. Does not start with your product \'97 starts with \\\
    their world. Strongest when the pain is specific and the brief has \\\
    high signal_strength.\
\
  outcome_led:\
    Opens with the result they could achieve, not the problem they have. \\\
    Aspirational framing. Works best when the prospect's likely KPIs are \\\
    clear and the proof point is strong. Weakest when proof is thin.\
\
  proof_led:\
    Opens with a named customer result that is directly relevant to this \\\
    prospect's industry or role. The relevance must be explicit \'97 \\\
    "a company like yours" is not proof-led, it is vague. \\\
    Requires a directly applicable proof point in the brief.\
\
  objection_prebunk:\
    Opens by acknowledging the most likely reason this prospect would \\\
    ignore this email, then immediately dismantling it. High-risk, \\\
    high-reward. Use when the brief reveals a likely objection and you \\\
    have a compelling counter.\
\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
YOUR INSTRUCTIONS\
\uc0\u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \u9552 \
\
STEP 1 \'97 SURVEY THE TERRAIN\
Before choosing angles, internally assess (do not include in output):\
  - What is the single strongest fact in the brief?\
  - What is the single strongest proof point?\
  - Is there a real timing signal or is this evergreen?\
  - What is this persona most likely to be worried about right now?\
  - What angle would feel most intrusive vs. most welcome to this person?\
\
This thinking shapes which angle types are even viable for this brief.\
\
STEP 2 \'97 DISQUALIFY BEFORE YOU BUILD\
Apply these disqualification rules before selecting angle types:\
\
  why_you_why_now: DISQUALIFIED if FitMap has no hypothesis with a \\\
    real why_now signal (i.e., all why_now fields say "No strong timing \\\
    signal"). Do not include this angle type.\
\
  proof_led: DISQUALIFIED if every hypothesis in the FitMap has a \\\
    "proof_gap" risk flag. Do not include this angle type.\
\
  objection_prebunk: DISQUALIFIED if brief.signal_strength is "low" \\\
    (not enough facts to credibly dismantle an objection). Do not include.\
\
  Document any disqualifications in a risk_flag: "angle_type_disqualified: \\\
    [reason]" on the angle that would have used it \'97 but do not include \\\
    that angle in the output.\
\
STEP 3 \'97 BUILD 3 TO 5 GENUINELY DISTINCT ANGLES\
For each angle:\
\
  angle_id: sequential \'97 angle_01, angle_02, etc.\
\
  angle_type: one of the five types above (only from qualified types)\
\
  rank: your honest assessment of which angle gives the best chance of \\\
    a reply from THIS prospect. 1 = strongest.\
\
  persona_fit_score: 0.0 to 1.0. How well does this angle match the \\\
    specific title, industry, and inferred priorities of this prospect? \\\
    Be calibrated. Do not score above 0.85 unless the brief is \\\
    exceptionally rich and specific.\
\
  selected_hook_id: the hook from the MessagingBrief that this angle \\\
    activates. Must exist in brief.hooks[].hook_id. If this angle uses \\\
    a FitMap hypothesis, the hook must match the hypothesis's \\\
    selected_hook_id or you must justify the deviation.\
\
  selected_fit_hypothesis_id: the FitMap hypothesis this angle is \\\
    built on. Must exist in fitmap.hypotheses[].fit_hypothesis_id.\
\
  pain: one sentence. The specific friction this angle leads with. \\\
    Even outcome_led and proof_led angles have an implicit pain \'97 \\\
    make it explicit here so Stage C has it available.\
\
  impact: one sentence. What that pain costs the prospect in \\\
    their own currency (time, revenue, missed targets, team stress).\
\
  value: one sentence. What the product does about it. No features \'97 \\\
    one clear outcome statement.\
\
  proof: the specific proof point this angle leans on. \\\
    If proof_gap applies, write: "No directly applicable proof \'97 \\\
    angle carries proof risk."\
\
  cta_question_suggestion: the natural question that this angle builds \\\
    toward. Should feel like the inevitable ask after this angle plays \\\
    out. Must be a question, not a statement. Must connect to the \\\
    locked CTA type in the brief. Max 160 characters.\
\
  risk_flags: inherited flags from FitMap hypothesis + any new flags \\\
    introduced by the angle itself. Empty array only if genuinely clean. \\\
    New flags to add if applicable:\
      "no_timing_signal_for_angle_type": angle type requires urgency \\\
        but none exists\
      "proof_risk": angle depends heavily on proof but proof_gap exists\
      "assumption_dependent": angle core is built on assumptions, not facts\
      "objection_requires_strong_rebuttal": only for objection_prebunk\
\
STEP 4 \'97 RANK WITH A TIE-BREAKING RULE\
Primary ranking: persona_fit_score \'d7 confidence (use FitMap hypothesis \\\
  confidence as a proxy)\
Tiebreaker 1: angle with real why_now signal ranks higher\
Tiebreaker 2: angle with directly applicable proof ranks higher\
Tiebreaker 3: angle with fewer risk flags ranks higher\
\
If you deviate from this formula, add a note in risk_flags: \\\
  "rank_override: [brief reason]"\
\
STEP 5 \'97 DISTINCTNESS CHECK\
Before outputting, verify:\
  [ ] No two angles open from the same entry point in the prospect's world\
  [ ] No two angles use the same selected_hook_id\
  [ ] No two angles have the same angle_type\
  [ ] At least one angle is ranked with honest skepticism \\\
      (persona_fit_score below 0.65) if brief signal_strength is \\\
      "medium" or "low"\
  [ ] Every selected_hook_id exists in brief.hooks[]\
  [ ] Every selected_fit_hypothesis_id exists in fitmap.hypotheses[]\
\
If the distinctness check fails for any pair, replace the weaker angle \\\
with a genuinely different approach before outputting.\
\
Now output the complete AngleSet JSON. Nothing else."""\
\
    return [\
        \{"role": "system", "content": system\},\
